04399nam a22006975i 9780824839239DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248392397 a10.1515/97808248392392doi  a(DE-B1597)484123  a(OCoLC)878078637  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4309512492231 aLim, Song Hwee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTsai Ming-liang and a Cinema of Slowness /cSong Hwee Lim. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b29 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Chinese Romanization, Translation, and Citation -- tIntroduction Going Slow -- tChapter 1. Slowness -- tChapter 2. Signature -- tChapter 3. Stillness -- tChapter 4. Silence -- tEpilogue Getting Lost -- tNotes -- tTsai Ming-Liang Filmography -- tGlossary of Chinese Terms -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow can we qualify slowness in cinema? What is the relationship between a cinema of slowness and a wider socio-cultural “slow movement”? A body of films that shares a propensity toward slowness has emerged in many parts of the world over the past two decades. This is the first book to examine the concept of cinematic slowness and address this fascinating phenomenon in contemporary film culture.Providing a critical investigation into questions of temporality, materiality, and aesthetics, and examining concepts of authorship, cinephilia, and nostalgia, Song Hwee Lim offers insight into cinematic slowness through the films of the Malaysian-born, Taiwan-based director Tsai Ming-liang. Through detailed analysis of aspects of stillness and silence in cinema, Lim delineates the strategies by which slowness in film can be constructed. By drawing on writings on cinephilia and the films of directors such as Abbas Kiarostami, Hou Hsiao-hsien, and Nuri Bilge Ceylan, he makes a passionate case for a slow cinema that calls for renewed attention to the image and to the experience of time in film.Tsai Ming-liang and a Cinema of Slowness will speak to readers with an interest in art cinema, queer studies, East Asian culture, and the question of time. In an age of unrelenting acceleration of pace both in film and in life, this book invites us to pause and listen, to linger and look, and, above all, to take things slowly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion pictureszTaiwanxHistory. 0aSlow cinema. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311075236640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483923940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824839239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824839239/original  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-075236-6  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK